  "response": "Ah, a great question that the show kind of...glossed over! While \"The Last Man on Earth\" was hilarious, the logistics of a global pandemic and its aftermath were often conveniently ignored. Here's the likely explanation, combining what the show hinted at and a bit of logical deduction:\n\n*   **The CDC/Government Clean Up Crews:** It's heavily implied that after the virus burned itself out, the CDC (or what was left of it) and perhaps elements of the military organized massive clean-up operations in major population centers. This would involve collecting and disposing of bodies to prevent further disease and to make areas habitable again. (For example, it's possible they burned bodies.) It would explain why Phil Miller (Tucson), Carol Pilbasian (Washington D.C.), and other characters were able to find relative clean areas to inhabit. This is the most plausible answer, especially in areas like major cities.\n\n*   **Nature Taking Its Course:** In less populated areas, it's likely that nature simply took over. Bodies would decompose, scavengers (animals, insects) would do their thing, and eventually, only skeletons would remain. The speed of decomposition would depend on climate and location.\n\n*   **Burning or Burying by Survivors (Pre-Show):** Before the show began and Phil Miller found Carol Pilbasian, it's possible that some survivors (those who were immune but later died due to other causes) might have tried to bury or burn the dead in their immediate vicinity, even if it was on a small scale.\n\n*   **The Show's Aversion to Gruesome Realism:** Ultimately, the biggest reason the show didn't delve into the bodies is that it was a comedy. Showing mass graves and decomposing bodies would have drastically changed the tone and made it a much darker, grimmer show. The writers consciously avoided the true horrors of a pandemic to maintain the comedic core.\n\n**In Conclusion:** The show never gives a definitive answer, but the most logical explanation is a combination of CDC/government clean-up crews (especially in urban areas) and natural decomposition. Also, the producers didn't want the show to be too grim.",
